    2:'''**Orthography**:
    
a - like 'ar' in the word 'h**ar**d' - /a/
e - like 'e' in the word 'sp**e**ll' - /e/
i - like the 'ee' in the word 's**ee**' - /i/
o - like the 'ar' in the word 'w**ar**d' - /o/
u - like the 'eu' in the french word 'bl**eu**' (blue) - /ɯ/
y - like the 'i' in the word 'th**i**s' - /ɪ/
w - like the 'oo' in the word 'z**oo**' /u/

k - 'c' in '**c**at' - /kʰ/
n - 'n' in '**n**o'  - /n/
p - 'p' in '**p**ass' - /pʰ/
t - 't' in '**t**oast' - /tʰ/
s - 's' in '**s**ew' - /s/
r - 'r' in '**r**ow' *or* the 'r' sound in the Japanese word 'ka**r**a' - /ɹ/ or /ɾ/
v - 'v' in '**v**itamin' - /v/
j - 'y' in '**y**ou' - /j/
lh - 'll' in the welsh word '**ll**anfairpw**ll**gwyngy**ll**gogerychwyrndroby**llll**tysiliogogogoch' (or the welsh word '**ll**an') - /ɬ/
l - 'l' in '**l**ove' - /l/
' - the sound in between the 'uh' and 'oh' in the phrase 'uh**-**oh'. Also the sound used instead of the 't' sound when British people drop their t's - /ʔ/
z - 'z' in '**z**oo' - /z/
g - 'g' in '**g**o' - /g/
h - 'h' in '**h**ave'; when at the end of a word or before a consonant, pronounced like the sound made when one is clearing their throat - /h/ at beginning, /χ/ at end
ph - 'th' in '**th**ing' - /θ/
bh - 'th' in '**th**is' - /ð/

NOTE:
- Combinations like 'er', 'ur', 'or' **do not** have the same sounds as their English counterparts. These sounds instead would be read as (using 'er' as an example) 'e' the 'r' as noted in the Kygish phonology
- 'w' is **never** pronounced like it is in English, it is always a vowel
- **'f', 'sh' and 'ch' do not exist in Kygish**, use 'ph', 's' and 't' instead when converting already existing English words into Kygish''',
